==English==

===Etymology===
* Variant of {{term|hollo}}, which was a variant of {{term|holla}}, from {{etyl|frm}} {{term|hola|lang=frm}}, equivalent to {{term|ho||lang=frm|ahoy}} + {{term|la||lang=frm|there}}. See also: [[holler]].

===Interjection===
{{en-interj}}

# A variant of '''[[hllo]]'''
# A cry of [[surprise]].
#* '''1890,''' [[w:Sir Arthur Conan Doyle|Sir Arthur Conan Doyle]], ''[[s:The Sign of the Four|The Sign of the Four]]'',
#*: It sounds like a sum in the rule of three. The answer should give us the — But '''hallo'''! here are the accredited representatives of the law.

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# The cry "hallo!"
# A shout of exultation.

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{intransitive}} To shout, or to call with a loud voice.
# {{transitive}} To chase while shouting "hallo!"
# {{transitive}} To cry "hallo" (to someone).
# {{transitive}} To shout (something).

